<BaseLayout title="About" description="About Konstantin Gredeskoul — engineering leader, open-source author, and applied-AI engineer.">
  <div class="about-layout">
    <div class="page">
      <div class="eyebrow">// about</div>
      <h1>Konstantin <em>Gredeskoul</em></h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Engineering leader and open-source author with 25+ years across distributed systems,
        scalability, and developer tooling — now focused on applied AI and AI-first engineering.
      </p>
      <div class="prose" style="margin-top:24px;">
        <p>
          I've spent my career making applications fast, resilient, and pleasant to operate —
          from scaling Wanelo on PostgreSQL to billions of rows, to writing open-source tools used
          millions of times over. These days I help teams integrate large language models, vector
          databases, and intelligent automation into production systems through
          <a href="https://reinvent.one">ReinventONE</a>.
        </p>
        <p>This blog is where I write up the engineering lessons in long form. A few numbers:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>200M+</strong> RubyGems downloads across my published gems</li>
          <li><strong>200+</strong> public GitHub repositories</li>
          <li><strong>200K+</strong> SlideShare views on talks and presentations</li>
          <li><strong>25+</strong> years building and scaling software</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Find me on <a href="https://github.com/kigster">GitHub</a>,
          <a href="https://twitter.com/kig">Twitter</a>, and
          <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/kigster">LinkedIn</a> — or
          <a href="https://cal.com/kigster-sf/connect">schedule a chat</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Want to hire me? Please checkout my <a href="/resume">resume</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <hr />

      <div class="prose" style="margin-top:24px;">
        <h1>More below, if you are still here :) </h1>

        <p clas="lead">Right now, Konstantin Gredeskul is building with AI — not talking about it at conferences, not writing thought pieces about prompt engineering, but shipping production systems that wire large language models, vector databases, and intelligent automation into applications that handle real traffic. Through ReinventONE, he consults, teaches, and deploys. On the side, he builds things like <a href="https://github.com/inquirex">Inquirex</a> — because open source is a habit he picked up decades ago and never kicked.</p>

        <p>Before the AI wave, there were the fires. At Fossa, he caught a PostgreSQL cluster creeping toward 27 terabytes of transaction ID wraparound — a silent, invisible catastrophe that would have bricked the entire database — and stopped it cold. At Wanelo, he took a Ruby application from 3,000 requests per minute to 300,000, scaling a social shopping platform through the kind of traffic that turns most Rails apps into smoking craters.</p>

        <p>His open-source footprint is absurd: 200 million+ RubyGems downloads, 200+ public GitHub repositories, tools running silently inside systems whose operators will never know his name.</p>

        <p>Rewind further and you find a kid in Kharkiv, Ukraine, winning math olympiads while the Soviet Union disintegrated around him. He taught himself C from whatever he could get his hands on, wrote production code before most engineers had heard of Linux, and spent the next thirty years proving that a self-taught mathematician with stubbornness and a terminal window can outbuild entire teams.</p>

        <p>But software has never been the whole story. He's been running whitewater rivers in a plastic kayak since he was thirteen. He plays piano, guitar, and drums — all at what he diplomatically calls an amateur level. He and his ex-wife produced two trip-hop and downtempo albums under the name PolyGroovers, available on every streaming platform worth opening.</p>

        <p>And then there's the thing no algorithm can touch. His daughter — one year old, absurdly adorable, and the brightest point in a life that has seen its share of darkness. He was born in Kharkiv, a city now under daily Russian bombardment. He lost family in the October 7th Hamas attack. The world he worries about is not abstract — it's personal, and it's on fire.</p>

        <p>He's not done yet. He's only started.</ p> 
      </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="author-aside">
      <img
      src="/assets/images/authors/kig-mid-size.png"
      alt="Konstantin Gredeskoul"
      width="256"
      height="256"
      />
    </aside>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
